			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Klast,
<br />

<br />
I think you are missing the point in a head long rush to judgement.
<br />

<br />
The "ban" has always existed. The problem is, the rules regarding photographic equipment in and around military installations simply have not been revised to include digital equipment including cellphones with video capability.
<br />

<br />
All Rummy is saying is that we have realized the potential security hole that these items present and will be including them in the rules regarding cameras both still and video. Military personnel who work in areas with retricted access all "know" (generally having signed a page 13 saying as much) that the use of video recording equipment is not allowed. In the Navy it is ok to have video recording equipment personal or otherwise on the ship, but everyone knows that even without film you don't take that equipmment into spaces such as CIC, Radio Central or any of the Intel spaces, because of the existing rules banning them from the spaces. Perhaps Rummy feels that if we cannot trust our troops to not violate the GC, we cannot trust them to follow the restrictions in place and that a total ban may be more effective.
<br />

<br />
Jumping to the conclusion that this is a "new" rule and is being instituted to cover up future transgressions is silly. If you think that the only changes ongoing in the military as a result of the prisoner abuse issues is this ban you are deluding yourself. The repercussions are affecting life throughout the military and the overall indifference to issues like this are getting heavy attention. I might add that the relative indifference toward training concerning issues like the GC are not due to the military not caring, but placing priorities on training to operations that are likely. Over the last 30 years the likelihood of the U.S. military holding large amounts of foreign prisoners has been very small and thus very low in the priority list for training. What many fail to understand is the huge amount of training that the military is required to accomplish day to day. We as members of the military are expected to know so much it is difficult to master it all and therefore we set priorities. Unfortunately it took the torture of these prisoners to throw a spot light on how crappy we did at setting them this time around. But then again it took the horrible fires on the USS Forrestal for the Navy to realize just how screwed damage control training was back then and make adjustments (which resonate in the training pipeline for every enlisted man/woman and officer to this day).
<br />

<br />
As far as editing goes, that has always happened. It is something we accept as a neccessary evil. The relatively edit free access the press had in the beginning of this Gulf War was unprecedented even considering the numerous journalists asked to leave the country due to breaking the relatively loose rules of release set by DoD this time around.
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
