				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">My list of dangerous rights was a response to Kulanae advising me of the dangers of a camera phone at the check out.  
<br />

<br />
You say a total ban may be the only way to ensure that security is not breached.  If you choose to look at it that way, then i guess you can do that.  The exposure of the torture pictures was a security breach.  I choose to look at it another way.  They are making sure that photographs are not used against them again.  George Bush stopped using Email when he became president.  The justice department Changed FOIA from release unless there is a reason not to, to deny unless successfully sued.  If the terrorists got in to GW's Email it would be a terrible security breach.  But is it more likely that terrorists would hack the Whitehouse Email servers, of that a court would subpoena the records?  Public records keep people honest.  That's why there are open meeting laws and the FOIA.  
<br />

<br />
To me the ruling on cameras means they fully intend to continue doing things that would horrify ordinary Americans.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
