				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">To me the ruling on cameras means they fully intend to continue doing things that would horrify ordinary Americans.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Again you missed the point. This is not new. The existence of the camera's in the prison in the first place was against the rules. The "ruling" simply re-inforces rules that already exist. 
<br />

<br />
Public records certainly keep people honest. Unfortunately the need to keep certain things out of the public record keeps people safe. I am not saying that the actual photograhps of abuse were in themselves a breach of security. What they are, is proof that a potential security problem exists in the form of camera phones. The ability of any Dick or Jane in the military, to take photos of sensitive infomation and or positions and transmit them instantaneously with very little probability of detection is a very serious issue. An issue that was not all that apparent until these pictures surfaced.
<br />

<br />
The decision has absolutely nothing to do with the content of the recorded data, but its existence in the face of regulations against it. Those photos should never have existed. Is it a good thing they did? That is a perspective issue. I really doubt that this abuse could have continued much longer if the claims of our most recent deserter are true. As Dd said the military cannot operate on the same set of rules as the civilian world. If we tried we would have such a massive break down of good order and discipline that we would cease to function entirely. 
<br />

<br />
We cannot afford to protect violators of security procedures in the military like we do the sources of sensitive journalistic items. The American public seems willing to protect the sources of leaks of the names of CIA agents in the guise of protecting journalistic sources. The military will not now or ever protect felons under this over protection of civil liberty abused by the media to protect their ability to garner information with shock value. If it requires tightening the standards in this area, so be it. 
<br />

<br />
Thank you for having faith that the military will police its own in this instance. Maybe you should come do my job for a week and see what is being done internally. It might open your eyes a little bit. Is it enough? Only time will tell, but I think the DoD is making a real good faith effort to ensure that there are no repeats of what happened, and in my opinion they are going to extremes to make the lesson painfully clear to everyone in the military.
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
