			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Kos,
<br />

<br />
Anytime a significant portion of the Gerneral Military training required of the force is targetted at a particular area, it makes a dramatic impact on day to day life. Obviously the extent of that impact is decided at the unit level and because of that it will be different from individual to individual. I cannot say exactly the extent to which it is affecting the typical soldier in the field, but I would imagine it is more dramatic than the once or twice a week it becomes an issue in my work. Again it falls to priorities, the likelihood of an Anti-submarine Tactical Air controller becoming responsible for the protection of prisoner rights borders on ridiculous, still I suffer through the training weekly. The likelidhood is much greater in the case of infantry soldiers in the Marine Corps and the Army and I would expect (though I have little evidence since my contact with them is almost non-existant) that they are subjected of late to daily training and or re-inforcement of the subject material. The DoD stance is that the abuse itself should not affect day to day operations and rightfully so. The average ground pounder in Iraq need only be aware of it, not entrenched in the problem. They have a job to do and that job must continue in the face of current problems. We cannot re-focus training of deployed units to the exclusion of their ability to perform their assigned task. Hindsight is 20/20, unfortunately we cannot stop, drop and roll here. The courts will do their job and the guilty will burn.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We in the military are Americans, and our actions must uphold the values of our country and the highest standards of professionalism and ethics. Our military code of conduct requires it, our nation demands it and the world expects it. Our culture of accountability and responsibility will accept nothing less.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
For most of us those are not just pretty words to make us feel better, nor is it a brushing off of the issue. Unfortunately when things like this happen, the entire military force shoulders the weight of responsibility for it. And we do. Recent efforts to hammer home the importance of our responsibility to adhere to the terms of treaties of which the U.S. is signatory to are the subject of daily issuance in the last few weeks and will continue even after more formal changes have been made to training requirements in the area. To date the extent of this training for the average soldier/sailor has been the memorization of our code of conduct. That among other things has been revisited military wide in recent weeks. My command, by direction, has also instituted general military training in the area that requires testing as proof of completion. That is pretty unheard of, so I think they might be taking it seriously.
<br />

<br />
The U.S. military is and always will be a reflection of the U.S. as a whole. The only difference is that each military member bears the additional weight of being an ambassador of his country to every foreign port he visits. The chain of command must make a concerted effort to ensure that the men and women under their command fulfill that roll in a positive manner. The unfortunate reality of the matter is that the actions of a select few cannot be foreseen nor prevented even with the best training. Like the quote said, we live a culture of accountablity and responsibility, but even that cannot prevent everything. 
<br />

<br />
So, round about, in response to your request for information Kos, the military has increased training across the board in the area of concern. Military members are in some instances and in the future probably in all areas, being required to attend mandatory training and signing letters of agreement or affirmation to understanding both our code of conduct and how it relates to the issues at hand. The responsible parties are being held responsible, those accountable parties are being held accountable (we make a definite distinction between the two and punish/award accordingly). Obviously I cannot release the text of the information I receive daily in the form of messages from all points in the COC from Rummy down to my fleet CINCs to force Master Chiefs etc, suffice it to say the volume of information on the subject is extensive.
<br />

<br />
Not too specific, but your request wasn't all that specific =P
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
