				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=128120&amp;sid=e1497d06ba2cbff51fe930a686a7f220#128120"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Mon May 24, 2004 2:17 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
				<td valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=128120&amp;sid=e1497d06ba2cbff51fe930a686a7f220"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When you speak to the other lifers, do you get the impression that they feel the media has shafted them? Or do you feel that they think someone got caught doing a bad thing? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
As with anything, both and neither and more. Opinions vary but two things hold very true with the "lifers" at my job (we are all lifers, my post is staffed by almost 100% carreer sailors mostly E-7 and up), and that is that the media handled it badly and that the suspects fucked up badly.
<br />

<br />
Most don't outright blame the media for a bad thing. What they are pissed about is what you mentioned - plastering the details and photos all over the world makes the soldiers job in Iraq just that much more dangerous. It simply adds fuel to a fire on the verge of being out of control.
<br />

<br />
Some disagreement exists in what many consider torture, but all agree that at best what was done was inappropriate. All of my colleagues agree that it was well outside the bounds of acceptable behavior and deserving of punishment via courts martial. We also realize the media could have handled their end of it better, but that the actions themselves set it all into motion. 
<br />

<br />
Personally I don't fault the media for the situation. I hold them responsible for what I consider irresponsible reporting. I believe strongly in the freedom of our press, what I do not agree with is the press having a get out of jail free card in every situation. If you divulge the identity of a CIA agent you are a felon. Release your source or go to jail. If you release a report in a situation that causes or has the propensity to cause (slippery slope part of it) grave damage to the U.S. or U.S. assests (taken from the wording of how security classifications are made) or incites either domestic violence against or external violence against U.S. personnel, military or civilian, you are a felon and should go to jail. Of course no law of that nature could ever happen, too damn hard to write laws that can be justly interpreted and applied on a case by case basis when they affect basic rights like freedom of speech.
<br />

<br />
As to who shafted who? The soldiers who committed these acts shafted the entire military. The best we can hope for is that proper disciplinary action is taken at all levels of responsibilty and punishments fitting the crimes are applied at the right level. But I wouldn't expect to here any of my peers saying the media shafted them. They simply did their job in an irresponsible manner consistent with what we as American allow and expect from our media.
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
