			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Public scrutiny of government operations is certainly a good thing on the whole and "secrets" should be really kept to an absolute minimum.  I would far prefer to see a culture of "need not to know" rather than "need to know" as far as freedom of information is concerned with respect to any government activity.
<br />

<br />
Lack of public scrutiny on any part of government leads to a belief that part of government is not subservient to the public at large.  Public scrutiny reminds people that "public servant" means exactly what it literally says.
<br />

<br />
Note that I'm not saying open everything up (that would be silly), but cultures of secrets and policies of "secret until proven otherwise" are ultimately counterproductive in many ways.  I've no idea if this is true or not in any part of government - just some random thoughts on freedoms and government accountability to the people.
<br />

<br />
Dd</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
