			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Dd,
<br />

<br />
I agree 100% that public scrutiny is needed. This incident really was never a need to know incident anyway. The problems with security / need to know and the abuses are totally separate issues actually. One issue just lead to the public knowledge of the other, but that doesn't make it right. 
<br />

<br />
Public scrutiny of military/government operation however can only go so far and not hinder the performance of those operations. I can only imagine how little would actually get done in our military and government with a press representative hovering around taking notes on absolutely everything. 
<br />

<br />
Need to know will always exist. Primarily for the same reasons the military is banning camera phones. The man power expended editing new photos/video and such to keep military movement, position, capabilites and intentions or as we know them Essential Elements of Friendly Information, with an open door policy to public scrutiny would definitely hamstring the military. We might as well just scrap the military as a whole at that point.
<br />

<br />
I agree as to freedom of information. If something does not threaten national security or have the tendency to harm the general public if made public, then it should be public knowledge. Military operations by their nature and the nature of the threat posed by the disclosure of them to the wrong people should never be public domain until after the fact. The American people elect representatives whose job it is to handle oversight of military operations for the civilian community. Senators and Congressional Representatives have that job, not the media, and personally, I prefer it that way.
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
