				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Anyone who finds themselves in possession of such documentation of mistreatment has an obligation to disseminate it. Consequences for the dissemination should be seen as ultimately the result of the action, not the act of revelation. Nobody who does such things should be able to rely on or expect secrecy to avoid consequences.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Anyone who finds themselves in possession of such documentation is legally obligated to turn that evidence over to the proper authority. In this case that authority would be the appropriate military command above the one in which the mistreatment took place. Alternatively the evidence could be provided directly to the appointed oversight agency or Congressional/Senate Armed Forces Committee. 
<br />

<br />
What you do not do is disseminate it to the world. Why? Because it is illegal to do so, and in this case it fuels a fire that we really don't want fueled. Common sense would tell you that this sort of informationl, if disseminated to the Arab world, would cause increased hostility toward your fellow soldiers and Americans. Following that common sense you would see that that increased hostility is going to lead to the deaths of some of those same people that might otherwise not happened. So the careless disregard of procedure in this case was criminally negligent and is in any case where releasing information that would tend to endanger or engender an hostile environment concerning the involved parties. 
<br />

<br />
I agree a whistleblower in this situation can be a hero and not a criminal, what I do not agree with is the whistleblower circumventing procedure and law to go about it. I also feel strongly that the situation need not have been broadcast around the worlds airwaves to be handled correctly. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Nobody who does such things should be able to rely on or expect secrecy to avoid consequences</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I don't think anyone has implied this in this thread. Nobody has much sympathy at all for the people who committed these acts. However, it is not the suspects who were put at higher risk due to the revelations, it was every soldier and American / non-Iraqi in Iraq that it affects. Had the information been turned over to the U.S. Inspector General I guarantee disciplinary and corrective actions would have been taken with great haste.
<br />

<br />
Is the whistleblower a hero? I guess that depends on perspective. I suspect the reasons for whistleblowing had less to do with defending the GC / basic human rights of the victims, than some other political motive. That is only my opinion, but generally when people refuse to follow procedure and do something illegal to point out something illegal it is because they have an ulterior motive.
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
