			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Oftentimes, and there are all too many documented cases of this, turning the information over to the "proper authority" would result in a coverup. I have no doubt that if this information wasn't made public through "inappropriate" channels it would also have been hushed up or ignored, just like the continuing abuse in Guantanamo has been.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Allegations and evidence are very different animals. You can see conspiracy all you want in the form of "cover up" when the result of an investigation into allegations does not fit your preconceived notion. But it is not the same as this situation. 
<br />

<br />
A true whistleblower with evidence always retains the ability to release information to different authority and ultimately publicly should they suspect no action is being taken based on the information provided to the proper authority. This is the logical path anyway, unfortunately when the evidence is used for political or other aims our passion for the dramatic and sensational requires public release. 
<br />

<br />
It is telling of this nation that we demand due process in legal matters but we also have no faith in the system to carry it out and demand public release of the details. How hard is it now going to be to find credible witnesses in this case after the main peice of evidence has been released to the world. Additionally most of the involved parties have made public statements concerning most aspects of any impending case. Any judge in his right mind would have gagged them and their lawyers immediately, unfortunately the full dissemination from the beginning made that impossible.
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
