			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Once again, there's a right thing to do, and a legal thing to do. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
No they are part of the same process. The <span style="font-weight: bold">right </span>thing to do simply needs to be done the legal way. The right thing and the legal way are not opposing things as you put it. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In a situation where abuses we're discussing are taking place, the proper authorities are the press, regardless of what the law says. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Bullshit. The media is never the "proper authority" for the initial release of evidence in any felony including human rights abuses. They are a point along the line, but they are not the starting point. We live in a society based on laws, we cannot willy nilly pick which ones we should obey and which we should disregard because they impede our ability to do the "right" thing. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The greater public interest always should take precedence when an human rights violations are concerned.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I would think the actual rights and right to justice of the victims would take precedence over "public interest". What public interest does the barrage of pictures and news reports serve outside the typical American need for sensational news? None that I can see. The only thing it accomplishes is more violence in responce. Tell me, do you believe your "public interest" is more important than the life of Nick Berg? The abuses shown in photos released by the media were cited as the direct reason for his execution. Done the right way those specific abuses would have remained unknown to the men who executed Nick Berg. Would they have killed him anyway? I don't know. The fact remains simply that releasing those photos to the world rather than quietly prosecuting the suspects, in the words of his killers, resulted in Nick Berg's death. Justify that with public interest please.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
