			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Tora,
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Done the right way those specific abuses would have remained unknown to the men who executed Nick Berg. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I find most of what you've said very thoughtful but I must take exception to that statement.  Done the right way, the offenders would be offered a speedy and public trial and Berg's assassins would still have heard about the abuses.  To say that those specific abuses would never have been part of the public record is most certainly the wrong thing to do and is usually termed a "cover up".
<br />

<br />
WIthout the threat of public scrutiny, any government agency (including the military) becomes a law unto itself and that's an unacceptable expenditure of public monies.
<br />

<br />
Within your statement is the implicit shifting of blame for the murder of Nick Berg from the assassins who performed the act to the media for reporting the catalyst.  Once you go down that path, you can follow the chain of catalysts all the way back to Bush for making the decision to go to war if you want because each step is as good as any other in a causal chain like that.  You then end up agreeing with Berg's father, which isn't exactly where I think you wanted to be.
<br />

<br />
Dd</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
