				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In a situation where abuses we're discussing are taking place, the proper authorities are the press, regardless of what the law says.  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Bullshit. The media is never the "proper authority" for the initial release of evidence in any felony including human rights abuses. They are a point along the line, but they are not the starting point. We live in a society based on laws, we cannot willy nilly pick which ones we should obey and which we should disregard because they impede our ability to do the "right" thing. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Anyone willing to torture or kill people is certainly willing to torture or kill <span style="font-style: italic">you</span>.  The same people also likely know the chain of escalation, and it may in fact already be compromised.  There is no willy-nilly about this.  Stopping at or ignoring a traffic light isn't a moral decision.  Exposing torturers by rapid dissemination of all evidence not only stops the torture, but it also protects the whistle-blower.  We are a society of people, not of laws.  Laws are strong guidelines for society, with consequences for those who violate them.  I for one am certainly willing to risk consequences when something obviously wrong is taking place.  I suspect and hope others are willing to do the same, because fear of discovery, not faith in process, is ultimately what keeps these things from happening.
<br />

<br />
Policy-makers rely on process to see to it that policies are followed.  With me so far?  Here's the deal: <span style="font-style: italic">Policies that allow for people to be tortured are bad and need to be immediately changed.</span>  Following procedures put in place in these circumstances makes no sense![/i]</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
