				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I should also add here that the consequences for the soldiers <span style="font-style: italic">do</span> figure into my thinking.  I have several war veterans in my family, all of which are shamed by the actions which have occurred in the American military prisons.
<br />

<br />
The action which shamed them is the abuse, not the exposure of the abuse.  Turture and shaming of prisoners can only be prevented with the threat of exposure, not mere policy.  An enlightened policy makes such abuses very visible, and thus prevents them from occurring.  The policy set in Iraq and elsewhere was very secretive of prisoner treatment.  It is a tragic consequence of this that soldiers were able to fall into the predictable human behavior which we saw captured on film.  Were photographs of prisoner treatment permitted to be taken and disseminated by the international press community, the mistreatment of prisoners and subsequent shaming of my veteran relatives would never have occurred.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
