			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Despite your protests, Rsak, I can easily see a number of people on Rants talking about how Clinton or some other Democrat had shamed our military had pictures been released under the term of that hypothetical president.  As it stands, a Republican was in office, with Rumsfeld taking a well-documented personal hand in the operations of a couple of notorious military prisons.  Were Clinton in office, it would be him and not the press taking heat for the shaming of our military and the increased danger to our troups from an enraged population of Iraqis.
<br />

<br />
As it stands, though, it is Bush in office, and Rumsfeld who put procedures in place which protected details of the treatment of prisoners.  "Our side can do no wrong" mentality runs rampant on both sides of the fence, and people lose sight of the bigger picture because their political biases.  I'm not immune to this myself, but I do attempt to assess things using values instead of political lables.  I also use the "other guy" mental exercise I've been arguiing from.  If Clinton had been involved with this mess in his presidency, you'd better believe I'd be outraged at the event and the policymakers, and not the press.  The press certainly has its flaws, but preventing this sort of thing is why the protection of free speech and the press are as crucial to the world as they are.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
